<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-748-914  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 748 914.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  August 13 1990 v24 n33 p83(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Creating your own promotion: with enough incentive, you can writeyourself a new job description.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Vitiello, Jill.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The corporate ladder has become skewed since many companies in thecomputer industry have begun downsizing.andP;  Information systemprofessionals looking to get ahead must develop new strategies fordoing so.andP;  One method is to create a promotion by writing arevised job description.andP;  Creating a new job description can berisky, but there are three guiding principles that will increasethe chances of success.andP;  Make sure the timing is right.andP;  The job'sresponsibilities must have changed enough to merit a new jobdescription.andP;  The person the job reports to should be involvedwith the process, perhaps even undertaking part of the actualwriting of the description.andP;  Focus on the company's needs.andP;  Theremust be a need to fulfill or management will not be inclined tochange anything.andP;  It is important to identify characteristics thecompany values and show how the job can be changed to reflectthem.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     GuidelinesCareersComputer industryJob ResponsibilityPromotion of Employee.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>